[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] In computer science, **automatic programming** is a type of computer programming in which some mechanism generates a computer program, to allow human programmers to write the code at a higher abstraction level.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] There has been little agreement on the precise definition of automatic programming, mostly because its meaning has changed over time.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] David Parnas, tracing the history of "automatic programming" in published research, noted that in the 1940s it described automation of the manual process of punching paper tape.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] Later it referred to translation of high-level programming languages like Fortran and ALGOL.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] One of the earliest programs identifiable as a compiler is named Autocode.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] Program synthesis is one type of automatic programming where a procedure is created from scratch, based on mathematical requirements.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] Mildred Koss, an early UNIVAC programmer, explains: "Writing machine code involved several tedious steps—breaking down a process into discrete instructions, assigning specific memory locations to all the commands, and managing the I/O buffers.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] After following these steps to implement mathematical routines, a sub-routine library, and sorting programs, our task was to look at the larger programming process.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] We needed to understand how we might reuse tested code and have the machine help in programming.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] As we programmed, we examined the process and tried to think of ways to abstract these steps to incorporate them into higher-level language.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] The goal is to improve programmer productivity.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] It is often related to code-reuse topics such as component-based software engineering.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] Modern programming languages are well supported by tools like Json4Swift (Swift) and Json2Kotlin (Kotlin).
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] These application generators supported COBOL inserts and overrides.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] A macro processor, such as the C preprocessor, which replaces patterns in source code according to relatively simple rules, is a simple form of source-code generator.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] Source-to-source code generation tools also exist.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] Large language models such as ChatGPT are capable of generating a program's source code from a description of the program given in a natural language.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] Many relational database management systems (RDBMS) provide a function that will export the content of the database as SQL data definition queries, which may then be executed to re-import the tables and their data, or migrate them to another RDBMS.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] Some languages use *annotations* to generate source code and inject it.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] For example, this is done in Java and Kotlin using annotations, for example the Project Lombok library which runs at compile time with an annotation processor.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] There has been a C++ proposal to add token sequence injection using compile-time reflective programming (reflection).
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] A low-code development platform (LCDP) is software that provides an environment programmers use to create application software through graphical user interfaces and configuration instead of traditional computer programming.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] Vibe coding is a software development practice assisted by artificial intelligence (AI) where the software developer describes a project or task in a prompt to a large language model (LLM) which generates source code automatically.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] Vibe coding may involve accepting AI-generated code without thorough review of the output, instead relying on results and follow-up prompts to guide changes.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] The term was coined in February 2025 by computer scientist Andrej Karpathy, a co-founder of OpenAI and former AI leader at Tesla.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] Merriam-Webster listed the term in March 2025 as a "slang & trending" expression.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] It was named the *Collins English Dictionary* Word of the Year for 2025.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] Advocates of vibe coding say that it allows even amateur programmers to produce software without the extensive training and skills required for software engineering.
[src:simulink-embedded/automatic-programming] Critics point out a lack of accountability, maintainability, and an increased risk of introducing security vulnerabilities in the resulting software.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] In computer programming, **dataflow programming** is a programming paradigm that models a program as a directed graph of the data flowing between operations, thus implementing dataflow principles and architecture.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programming languages share some features of functional languages, and were generally developed in order to bring some functional concepts to a language more suitable for numeric processing.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Some authors use the term *datastream* instead of *dataflow* to avoid confusion with dataflow computing or dataflow architecture, based on an indeterministic machine paradigm.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programming was pioneered by Jack Dennis and his graduate students at MIT in the 1960s.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Traditionally, a program is modelled as a series of operations happening in a specific order; this may be referred to as sequential, procedural, control flow (indicating that the program chooses a specific path), or imperative programming.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] The program focuses on commands, in line with the von Neumann vision of sequential programming, where data is normally "at rest".
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] In contrast, dataflow programming emphasizes the movement of data and models programs as a series of connections.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Explicitly defined inputs and outputs connect operations, which function like black boxes.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] An operation runs as soon as all of its inputs become valid.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Thus, dataflow languages are inherently parallel and can work well in large, decentralized systems.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] One of the key concepts in computer programming is the idea of state, essentially a snapshot of various conditions in the system.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Most programming languages require a considerable amount of state information, which is generally hidden from the programmer.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Often, the computer itself has no idea which piece of information encodes the enduring state.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] This is a serious problem, as the state information needs to be shared across multiple processors in parallel processing machines.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Most languages force the programmer to add extra code to indicate which data and parts of the code are important to the state.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] This code tends to be both expensive in terms of performance, as well as difficult to read or debug.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Explicit parallelism is one of the main reasons for the poor performance of Enterprise Java Beans when building data-intensive, non-OLTP applications.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Where a sequential program can be imagined as a single worker moving between tasks (operations), a dataflow program is more like a series of workers on an assembly line, each doing a specific task whenever materials are available.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Since the operations are only concerned with the availability of data inputs, they have no hidden state to track, and are all "ready" at the same time.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programs are represented in different ways.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] A traditional program is usually represented as a series of text instructions, which is reasonable for describing a serial system which pipes data between small, single-purpose tools that receive, process, and return.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programs start with an input, perhaps the command line parameters, and illustrate how that data is used and modified.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] The flow of data is explicit, often visually illustrated as a line or pipe.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] In terms of encoding, a dataflow program might be implemented as a hash table, with uniquely identified inputs as the keys, used to look up pointers to the instructions.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] When any operation completes, the program scans down the list of operations until it finds the first operation where all inputs are currently valid, and runs it.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] When that operation finishes, it will typically output data, thereby making another operation become valid.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] For parallel operation, only the list needs to be shared; it is the state of the entire program.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Thus the task of maintaining state is removed from the programmer and given to the language's runtime.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] On machines with a single processor core where an implementation designed for parallel operation would simply introduce overhead, this overhead can be removed completely by using a different runtime.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Some recent dataflow libraries such as Differential/Timely Dataflow have used incremental computing for much more efficient data processing.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] A pioneer dataflow language was BLOck DIagram (BLODI), published in 1961 by John Larry Kelly, Jr., Carol Lochbaum and Victor A.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Vyssotsky for specifying sampled data systems.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] A BLODI specification of functional units (amplifiers, adders, delay lines, etc.) and their interconnections was compiled into a single loop that updated the entire system for one clock tick.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] In a 1966 Ph.D. thesis, *The On-line Graphical Specification of Computer Procedures*, Bert Sutherland created one of the first graphical dataflow programming frameworks in order to make parallel programming easier.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Subsequent dataflow languages were often developed at the large supercomputer labs.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] SISAL, a popular dataflow language developed at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, looks like most statement-driven languages, but variables should be assigned once.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] This allows the compiler to easily identify the inputs and outputs.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] A number of offshoots of SISAL have been developed, including SAC, *Single Assignment C*, which tries to remain as close to the popular C programming language as possible.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] The United States Navy funded development of signal processing graph notation (SPGN) and ACOS starting in the early 1980s.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] This is in use on a number of platforms in the field today.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] A more radical concept is Prograph, in which programs are constructed as graphs onscreen, and variables are replaced entirely with lines linking inputs to outputs.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] Prograph was originally written on the Macintosh, which remained single-processor until the introduction of the DayStar Genesis MP in 1996.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] There are many hardware architectures oriented toward the efficient implementation of dataflow programming models.
[src:simulink-embedded/dataflow-programming] MIT's tagged token dataflow architecture was designed by Greg Papadopoulos.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] A precise and stable characteristic feature is that no or not all functions of embedded software are initiated/controlled via a human interface, but through machine-interfaces instead.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Manufacturers build embedded software into the electronics of cars, telephones, modems, robots, appliances, toys, security systems, pacemakers, televisions and set-top boxes, and digital watches, for example.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] This software can be very simple, such as lighting controls running on an 8-bit microcontroller with a few kilobytes of memory with the suitable level of processing complexity determined with a Probably Approximately Correct Computation framework (a methodology based on randomized algorithms).
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] However, embedded software can become very sophisticated in applications such as routers, optical network elements, airplanes, missiles, and process control systems.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Unlike standard computers that generally use operating systems such as macOS, Windows or Linux, embedded software may use no operating system.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] When they do use one, a wide variety of operating systems can be chosen from, typically a real-time operating system.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Code for embedded software is typically written in C or C++, but various high-level programming languages, such as C#, Java, Python and JavaScript, are now also in common use to target microcontrollers and embedded systems.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Assembly languages are often used too, especially in booting and interrupt handling.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Ada is used in some military and aviation projects.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Most consumers are familiar with application software that provide functionality on a computer.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] However embedded software is often less visible, but no less complicated.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Unlike application software, embedded software has fixed hardware requirements and capabilities, and addition of third-party hardware or software is strictly controlled.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Embedded software needs to include all needed device drivers at manufacturing time, and the device drivers are written for the various hardware devices.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] The software is highly dependent on the CPU and specific chips chosen.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Most embedded software engineers have at least a passing knowledge of reading schematics, and reading data sheets for components to determine usage of registers and communication system.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Conversion between decimal, hexadecimal and binary is useful as well as using bit manipulation.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Web applications are often used for managing hardware, although XML files and other output may be passed to a computer for display.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] File systems with folders are typically used, however SQL databases are often absent.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Software development requires use of a cross compiler, which runs on a computer but produces executable code for the target device.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Debugging requires use of an in-circuit emulator, and debugging hardware such as JTAG or SWD debuggers.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Software developers often have access to the complete kernel (OS) source code.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Size of the storage memory and RAM can vary significantly.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Some systems run in 16 KB of Flash and 4 KB of RAM with a CPU operating at 8 MHz, other systems can rival contemporary computers.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] These space requirements lead to more work being done in C or embedded C++, instead of C++.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Interpreted languages like BASIC (while e.g.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Parallax Propeller can use compiled BASIC) and Java (Java ME Embedded 8.3 is available for e.g.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] ARM Cortex-M4, Cortex-M7 microcontrollers and older ARM11 used in Raspberry Pi and Intel Galileo Gen.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] 2) are not commonly used; while an implementation of the interpreted Python 3 language – MicroPython – is however available expressly for microcontroller use, e.g.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] 32-bit ARM-based (such as BBC micro:bit) and 16-bit PIC microcontrollers.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Communications between processors and between one processor and other components are essential.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Besides direct memory addressing, hardware level common protocols include I²C, SPI, serial ports, 1-Wires, Ethernets, and USB.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Communications protocols designed for use in embedded systems are available as closed source from companies including InterNiche Technologies and CMX Systems.
[src:simulink-embedded/embedded-software] Open-source protocols stem from uIP, lwip, and others.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Although MATLAB is intended primarily for numeric computing, an optional toolbox uses the MuPAD symbolic engine allowing access to symbolic computing abilities.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] An additional package, Simulink, adds graphical multi-domain simulation and model-based design for dynamic and embedded systems.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] As of 2020, MATLAB has more than four million users worldwide.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] They come from various backgrounds of engineering, science, and economics.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] As of 2017, more than 5000 global colleges and universities use MATLAB to support instruction and research.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] MATLAB was invented by mathematician and computer programmer Cleve Moler.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] The idea for MATLAB was based on his 1960s PhD thesis.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Moler became a math professor at the University of New Mexico and started developing MATLAB for his students as a hobby.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] He developed MATLAB's initial linear algebra programming in 1967 with his one-time thesis advisor, George Forsythe.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] This was followed by Fortran code for linear equations in 1971.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Before version 1.0, MATLAB "was not a programming language; it was a simple interactive matrix calculator.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] There were no programs, no toolboxes, no graphics.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] The first early version of MATLAB was completed in the late 1970s.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] The software was disclosed to the public for the first time in February 1979 at the Naval Postgraduate School in California.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Early versions of MATLAB were simple matrix calculators with 71 pre-built functions.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] At the time, MATLAB was distributed for free to universities.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Moler would leave copies at universities he visited and the software developed a strong following in the math departments of university campuses.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] They decided to reprogram MATLAB in C and market it for the IBM desktops that were replacing mainframe computers at the time.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] John Little and programmer Steve Bangert re-programmed MATLAB in C, created the MATLAB programming language, and developed features for toolboxes.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] MATLAB was first released as a commercial product in 1984 at the Automatic Control Conference in Las Vegas.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] MathWorks, Inc. was founded to develop the software and the MATLAB programming language was released.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] The first MATLAB sale was the following year, when Nick Trefethen from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology bought ten copies.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] By the end of the 1980s, several hundred copies of MATLAB had been sold to universities for student use.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] The software was popularized largely thanks to toolboxes created by experts in various fields for performing specialized mathematical tasks.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Many of the toolboxes were developed as a result of Stanford students that used MATLAB in academia, then brought the software with them to the private sector.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Over time, MATLAB was re-written for early operating systems created by Digital Equipment Corporation, VAX, Sun Microsystems, and for Unix PCs.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] The first MATLAB compiler was developed by Stephen C.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] In 2000, MathWorks added a Fortran-based library for linear algebra in MATLAB 6, replacing the software's original LINPACK and EISPACK subroutines that were in C.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] MATLAB's Parallel Computing Toolbox was released at the 2004 Supercomputing Conference and support for graphics processing units (GPUs) was added to it in 2010.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Some especially large changes to the software were made with version 8 in 2012.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] The user interface was reworked and Simulink's functionality was expanded.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] By 2016, MATLAB had introduced several technical and user interface improvements, including the MATLAB Live Editor notebook, and other features.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] For a complete list of changes of both MATLAB an official toolboxes, check MATLAB previous releases.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] The MATLAB application is built around the MATLAB programming language.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Common usage of the MATLAB application involves using the "Command Window" as an interactive mathematical shell or executing text files containing MATLAB code.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] An example of a "Hello, world!" program exists in MATLAB.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Variables are defined using the assignment operator, `=`.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] MATLAB is a weakly typed programming language because types are implicitly converted.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] It is an inferred typed language because variables can be assigned without declaring their type, except if they are to be treated as symbolic objects, and that their type can change.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Values can come from constants, from computation involving values of other variables, or from the output of a function.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] A simple array is defined using the colon syntax: *initial*`:`*increment*`:`*terminator*.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] defines a variable named `array` (or assigns a new value to an existing variable with the name `array`) which is an array consisting of the values 1, 3, 5, 7, and 9.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] That is, the array starts at 1 (the *initial* value), increments with each step from the previous value by 2 (the *increment* value), and stops once it reaches (or is about to exceed) 9 (the *terminator* value).
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] The *increment* value can actually be left out of this syntax (along with one of the colons), to use a default value of 1.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] assigns to the variable named `ari` an array with the values 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5, since the default value of 1 is used as the increment.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Indexing is one-based, which is the usual convention for matrices in mathematics, unlike zero-based indexing commonly used in other programming languages such as C, C++, and Java.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Matrices can be defined by separating the elements of a row with blank space or comma and using a semicolon to separate the rows.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] The list of elements should be surrounded by square brackets `[]`.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Parentheses `()` are used to access elements and subarrays (they are also used to denote a function argument list).
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Sets of indices can be specified by expressions such as `2:4`, which evaluates to `[2, 3, 4]`.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] A square identity matrix of size *n* can be generated using the function `eye`, and matrices of any size with zeros or ones can be generated with the functions `zeros` and `ones`, respectively.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Most functions accept arrays as input and operate element-wise on each element.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] For example, `mod(2*J,n)` will multiply every element in *J* by 2, and then reduce each element modulo *n*.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] MATLAB does include standard `for` and `while` loops, but (as in other similar applications such as APL and R), using the vectorized notation is encouraged and is often faster to execute.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Since all variables in MATLAB are arrays, a more adequate name is "structure array", where each element of the array has the same field names.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] In addition, MATLAB supports dynamic field names (field look-ups by name, field manipulations, etc.).
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] When creating a MATLAB function, the name of the file should match the name of the first function in the file.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Valid function names begin with an alphabetic character, and can contain letters, numbers, or underscores.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Variables and functions are case sensitive.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] MATLAB supports elements of lambda calculus by introducing function handles, or function references, which are implemented either in .m files or anonymous/nested functions.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] MATLAB supports object-oriented programming including classes, inheritance, virtual dispatch, packages, pass-by-value semantics, and pass-by-reference semantics.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] However, the syntax and calling conventions are significantly different from other languages.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] MATLAB has value classes and reference classes, depending on whether the class has *handle* as a super-class (for reference classes) or not (for value classes).
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Method call behavior is different between value and reference classes.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] can alter any member of *object* only if *object* is an instance of a reference class, otherwise value class methods must return a new instance if it needs to modify the object.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] MATLAB has tightly integrated graph-plotting features.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] For example, the function *plot* can be used to produce a graph from two vectors *x* and *y*.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] MATLAB supports developing graphical user interface (GUI) applications.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] UIs can be generated either programmatically or using visual design environments such as *GUIDE* and *App Designer*.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] MATLAB can call functions and subroutines written in the programming languages C or Fortran.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] A wrapper function is created allowing MATLAB data types to be passed and returned.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] MEX files (MATLAB executables) are the dynamically loadable object files created by compiling such functions.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Since 2014 increasing two-way interfacing with Python was being added.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Libraries written in Perl, Java, ActiveX or .NET can be directly called from MATLAB, and many MATLAB libraries (for example XML or SQL support) are implemented as wrappers around Java or ActiveX libraries.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Calling MATLAB from Java is more complicated, but can be done with a MATLAB toolbox which is sold separately by MathWorks, or using an undocumented mechanism called JMI (Java-to-MATLAB Interface), (which should not be confused with the unrelated Java Metadata Interface that is also called JMI).
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Official MATLAB API for Java was added in 2016.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] As alternatives to the MuPAD based Symbolic Math Toolbox available from MathWorks, MATLAB can be connected to Maple or Mathematica.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] Libraries also exist to import and export MathML.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] In 2020, MATLAB withdrew services from two Chinese universities as a result of US sanctions.
[src:simulink-embedded/matlab] The universities said this will be responded to by increased use of open-source alternatives and by developing domestic alternatives.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Model-based design provides an efficient approach for establishing a common framework for communication throughout the design process while supporting the development cycle (V-model).
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] 4. integrating all these phases by deploying the controller.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] The model-based design is significantly different from traditional design methodology.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Rather than using complex structures and extensive software code, designers can use Model-based design to define plant models with advanced functional characteristics using continuous-time and discrete-time building blocks.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] These built models used with simulation tools can lead to rapid prototyping, software testing, and verification.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Not only is the testing and verification process enhanced, but also, in some cases, hardware-in-the-loop simulation can be used with the new design paradigm to perform testing of dynamic effects on the system more quickly and much more efficiently than with traditional design methodology.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] As early as the 1920s two aspects of engineering, control theory and control systems, converged to make large-scale integrated systems possible.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] In those early days controls systems were commonly used in the industrial environment.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Large process facilities started using process controllers for regulating continuous variables such as temperature, pressure, and flow rate.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Electrical relays built into ladder-like networks were one of the first discrete control devices to automate an entire manufacturing process.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Control systems gained momentum, primarily in the automotive and aerospace sectors.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] In the 1950s and 1960s, the push to space generated interest in embedded control systems.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Engineers constructed control systems such as engine control units and flight simulators, that could be part of the end product.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] By the end of the twentieth century, embedded control systems were ubiquitous, as even major household consumer appliances such as washing machines and air conditioners contained complex and advanced control algorithms, making them much more "intelligent".
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] In 1969, the first computer-based controllers were introduced.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] These early programmable logic controllers (PLC) mimicked the operations of already available discrete control technologies that used the out-dated relay ladders.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] The advent of PC technology brought a drastic shift in the process and discrete control market.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] An off-the-shelf desktop loaded with adequate hardware and software can run an entire process unit, and execute complex and established PID algorithms or work as a Distributed Control System (DCS).
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] The mathematical model conceived in step 1 is used to identify dynamic characteristics of the plant model.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] A controller can then be synthesized based on these characteristics.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Offline simulation and real-time simulation.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] The time response of the dynamic system to complex, time-varying inputs is investigated.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] This is done by simulating a simple LTI (Linear Time-Invariant) model, or by simulating a non-linear model of the plant with the controller.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Simulation allows specification, requirements, and modeling errors to be found immediately, rather than later in the design effort.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Real-time simulation can be done by automatically generating code for the controller developed in step 2.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] This code can be deployed to a special real-time prototyping computer that can run the code and control the operation of the plant.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] If a plant prototype is not available, or testing on the prototype is dangerous or expensive, code can be automatically generated from the plant model.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] This code can be deployed to the special real-time computer that can be connected to the target processor with running controller code.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Thus a controller can be tested in real-time against a real-time plant model.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Ideally this is done via code generation from the controller developed in step 2.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] It is unlikely that the controller will work on the actual system as well as it did in simulation, so an iterative debugging process is carried out by analyzing results on the actual target and updating the controller model.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Model-based design tools allow all these iterative steps to be performed in a unified visual environment.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] The disadvantages of model-based design are fairly well understood this late in development lifecycle of the product and development.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] While Model-based design has the ability to simulate test scenarios and interpret simulations well, in real world production environments, it is often not suitable.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Over reliance on a given toolchain can lead to significant rework and possibly compromise entire engineering approaches.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] While it's suitable for bench work, the choice to use this for a production system should be made very carefully.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Because of the limitations of graphical tools, design engineers previously relied heavily on text-based programming and mathematical models.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] However, developing these models was time-consuming, and highly prone to error.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] In addition, debugging text-based programs is a tedious process, requiring much trial and error before a final fault-free model could be created, especially since mathematical models undergo unseen changes during the translation through the various design stages.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Graphical modeling tools aim to improve these aspects of design.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] These tools provide a very generic and unified graphical modeling environment, and they reduce the complexity of model designs by breaking them into hierarchies of individual design blocks.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Designers can thus achieve multiple levels of model fidelity by simply substituting one block element with another.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Graphical models also help engineers to conceptualize the entire system and simplify the process of transporting the model from one stage to another in the design process.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] Boeing's simulator EASY5 was among the first modeling tools to be provided with a graphical user interface, together with AMESim, a multi-domain, multi-level platform based on the Bond Graph theory.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] This was soon followed by tool like 20-sim and Dymola, which allowed models to be composed of physical components like masses, springs, resistors, etc.
[src:simulink-embedded/model-based-design] These were later followed by many other modern tools such as Simulink and LabVIEW.
[src:simulink-embedded/simulink] MathWorks and other third-party hardware and software products can be used with Simulink.
[src:simulink-embedded/simulink] For example, Stateflow extends Simulink with a design environment for developing state machines and flow charts.
[src:simulink-embedded/simulink] Simscape is an add-on product that extends Simulink with support for physical modeling.
[src:simulink-embedded/simulink] Developed by MathWorks, it enables the modeling and simulation of multidomain physical systems by connecting physical components whose interactions represent domains such as electrical, mechanical, thermal, and fluid systems.
[src:simulink-embedded/simulink] Simscape models can be combined with standard Simulink block diagrams, allowing the simulation of systems that couple physical dynamics with control algorithms and signal-based components.
[src:simulink-embedded/simulink] Coupled with another of their products, Simulink can automatically generate C source code for real-time implementation of systems.
[src:simulink-embedded/simulink] As the efficiency and flexibility of the code improves, this is becoming more widely adopted for production systems, in addition to being a tool for embedded system design work because of its flexibility and capacity for quick iteration.
[src:simulink-embedded/simulink] Embedded Coder creates code efficient enough for use in embedded systems.
[src:simulink-embedded/simulink] Simulink Real-Time (formerly known as xPC Target), together with x86-based real-time systems, is an environment for simulating and testing Simulink and Stateflow models in real-time on the physical system.
[src:simulink-embedded/simulink] Another MathWorks product also supports specific embedded targets.
[src:simulink-embedded/simulink] When used with other generic products, Simulink and Stateflow can automatically generate synthesizable VHDL and Verilog.
[src:simulink-embedded/simulink] Simulink Verification and Validation enables systematic verification and validation of models through modeling style checking, requirements traceability and model coverage analysis.
[src:simulink-embedded/simulink] Simulink Design Verifier uses formal methods to identify design errors like integer overflow, division by zero and dead logic, and generates test case scenarios for model checking within the Simulink environment.
[src:simulink-embedded/simulink] SimEvents is used to add a library of graphical building blocks for modeling queuing systems to the Simulink environment, and to add an event-based simulation engine to the time-based simulation engine in Simulink.
